```java
class PowerOfThree {
    static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        // Checking edge case: non-integer values & zero
        if (!(n >= -231 && n <= 231 - 1)) return false;
        if (n == 0) return false;

        // Using bitwise operation to check if only one '1' in binary representation shifted by odd positions
        return ((n > 0 && (n & n - 1) == 0) && Integer.bitCount(Integer.reverseBits(n)) == 1);
    }
}
```
This method works because powers of three have a unique pattern in their binary representation – they contain a single '1', which is shifted to an odd position when represented in two's complement form (either leftmost or after an even number of zeros). The `Integer#reverseBits()` method flips the bits while keeping the same value, making the '1' appear at the rightmost side. Then `Integer#bitCount()` counts the number of set bits, which should be exactly 1 for our condition to hold true. Finally, we ensure `n > 0`, as per the constraint range `[-231, 231 - 1]`. This solution handles all cases except zero within the stated constraints.

